{"type":"message","id":"303da8c2","parentId":"0f17be61","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:01:13.247Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_m9kv8inbzlelwbvodegybxdg","toolName":"web_crawl","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"url\": \"https://github.com/Intense-Visions/harness-engineering/blob/main/AGENTS.md\",\n  \"content\": \"/ Public\\n\\n- \\n\\n- \\n\\n- \\n\\n- \\n\\n- \\n\\n- \\n\\n## FilesExpand file tree\\n\\nmain\\n\\n## Breadcrumbs\\n\\n1. \\n\\n/\\n\\n# AGENTS.md\\n\\nCopy path\\n\\n590 lines (412 loc) · 20.7 KB\\n\\n1. \\n\\n/\\n\\n# AGENTS.md\\n\\n590 lines (412 loc) · 20.7 KB\\n\\n# Harness Engineering: AI Agent Knowledge Map\\n\\nThis is the single source of truth for AI agents working on the Harness Engineering project. It provides essential context about our repository structure, architecture, conventions, and where to find information.\\n\\n## Project Overview\\n\\n**Harness Engineering**  is a comprehensive toolkit for transitioning from manual coding to **agent-first development** . We help teams architect software in ways that enable AI agents to execute, maintain, and improve code reliably and autonomously.\\n\\n### Purpose and Goals\\n\\n- Create a reusable library and toolkit for agent-first development\\n\\n- Establish patterns that make AI-driven development predictable and scalable\\n\\n- Document architectural decisions as the single source of truth\\n\\n- Enforce constraints mechanically rather than through code review\\n\\n- Measure and improve agent autonomy over time\\n\\n### Current Phase\\n\\n**Complete**  — All core packages (types, core, cli, eslint-plugin, linter-gen, graph, orchestrator), 49 skills (claude-code) / 49 skills (gemini-cli), 12 personas, 6 templates, and 3 progressive examples are implemented. The project is in adoption and refinement mode. See `examples/` for progressive tutorials.\\n\\n## Repository Structure\\n\\nThis is a **monorepo**  using pnpm workspaces and Turborepo for orchestration.\\n\\n```\\nharness-engineering/\\n├── packages/ # Core application packages\\n│ ├── types/ # Shared TypeScript types and interfaces\\n│ ├── core/ # Core runtime library and utilities\\n│ ├── cli/ # CLI tool (harness validate, check-deps, skill, state, etc.)\\n│ ├── eslint-plugin/ # ESLint rules for constraint enforcement\\n│ ├── linter-gen/ # YAML-to-ESLint rule generator\\n│ ├── graph/ # Unified Knowledge Graph: LokiJS store, ContextQL queries, code/git/knowledge ingestion, FusionLayer search, 4 external connectors (Jira, Slack, Confluence, CI)\\n│ └── orchestrator/ # Agent orchestration daemon for dispatching coding agents to issues\\n├── agents/ # Agent configuration\\n│ ├── skills/claude-code/ # 49 skills (skill.yaml + SKILL.md each)\\n│ ├── skills/gemini-cli/ # 49 skills (adapted for Gemini CLI, includes sensitive-data-compliance)\\n│ └── personas/ # 12 personas (architecture-enforcer, code-reviewer, codebase-health-analyst, documentation-maintainer, entropy-cleaner, graph-maintainer, parallel-coordinator, performance-guardian, planner, security-reviewer, task-executor, verifier)\\n├── templates/ # Project scaffolding templates (base, basic, intermediate, advanced, nextjs, orchestrator)\\n├── examples/ # Progressive tutorial examples\\n│ ├── hello-world/ # Basic adoption level\\n│ ├── task-api/ # Intermediate adoption level\\n│ └── multi-tenant-api/ # Advanced adoption level\\n├── docs/ # Complete documentation suite\\n│ ├── standard/ # Harness Engineering principles and standard\\n│ ├── guides/ # How-to guides and tutorials\\n│ ├── reference/ # Configuration and API reference\\n│ ├── specs/ # Detailed technical specifications\\n│ ├── plans/ # Implementation and execution plans\\n│ ├── research/ # Framework research and analysis\\n│ ├── conventions/ # Format conventions (markdown interaction patterns)\\n│ └── changes/ # Design change proposals and deltas\\n├── package.json # Root package metadata and scripts\\n├── tsconfig.json # Root TypeScript configuration\\n├── pnpm-workspace.yaml # pnpm workspace definition\\n├── turbo.json # Turborepo configuration\\n└── AGENTS.md # This file - AI agent knowledge map\\n```\\n### Package Relationships\\n\\n- **types**  → Shared type definitions (no dependencies)\\n\\n- **core**  → Runtime library (depends on types)\\n\\n- **graph**  → Knowledge graph for codebase relationships and entropy detection (depends on types)\\n\\n- **orchestrator**  → Agent orchestration and multi-agent coordination (depends on core)\\n\\n- All packages follow strict dependency rules: no circular dependencies, no upward dependencies\\n\\n## Architecture\\n\\n### Layered Architecture\\n\\nWe follow a strict, one-way dependency model:\\n\\n```\\nTypes (bottom layer - no dependencies)\\n ↓\\nConfiguration & Constants\\n ↓\\nRepository & Data Access\\n ↓\\nServices & Business Logic\\n ↓\\nAgents & External Interfaces (top layer)\\n```\\n**Key Rule** : Layers can only depend on lower layers, never upward.\\n\\n### Design Decisions\\n\\n1. **TypeScript Strict Mode**  - All code runs with strict type checking enabled\\n\\n2. **Project References**  - We use tsconfig project references for proper compilation order and dependency validation\\n\\n3. **Monorepo Structure**  - Enables shared code and consistent tooling across packages\\n\\n4. **Documentation-First**  - All architectural decisions live in git as version-controlled markdown\\n\\n5. **Result<T, E> Pattern**  - Explicit error handling using Result types (similar to Rust's Result)\\n\\n### Module Boundaries\\n\\nEach package has a clear responsibility:\\n\\n- **types** : Type definitions, interfaces, and constants used across packages\\n\\n- **core** : Runtime library with validation, utilities, and common functionality\\n\\n- See package.json files in each package for full dependency details.\\n\\n## Development Workflow\\n\\n### Prerequisites\\n\\nEnsure you have these tools installed:\\n\\n- **Node.js 22+**  - Download from \\n\\n- **pnpm 8+**  - Install with: `npm install -g pnpm`\\n\\n- **Git**  - Required for version control\\n\\nVerify your setup:\\n\\n```\\nnode --version # Should be 22.x or higher\\npnpm --version # Should be 8.x or higher\\ngit --version # Any recent version\\n```\\n### Setting Up the Project\\n\\n```\\n# 1. Clone the repository\\ngit clone https://github.com/Intense-Visions/harness-engineering.git\\ncd harness-engineering\\n\\n# 2. Install all dependencies\\npnpm install\\n\\n# 3. Verify the setup by building\\npnpm build\\n\\n# 4. Run tests to ensure everything works\\npnpm test\\n```\\n### Common Development Tasks\\n\\n```\\n# Install dependencies\\npnpm install\\n\\n# Build all packages\\npnpm build\\n\\n# Watch mode for development\\npnpm dev\\n\\n# Run all tests\\npnpm test\\n\\n# Run tests in watch mode\\npnpm test:watch\\n\\n# Run tests for a specific package\\npnpm test --filter=@harness-engineering/core\\n\\n# Lint all code\\npnpm lint\\n\\n# Format code (TypeScript, JavaScript, Markdown, JSON)\\npnpm format\\n\\n# Check formatting without making changes\\npnpm format:check\\n\\n# Type checking\\npnpm typecheck\\n\\n# Start documentation server\\npnpm docs:dev\\n\\n# Build documentation\\npnpm docs:build\\n\\n# Preview built documentation\\npnpm docs:preview\\n\\n# Clean build artifacts\\npnpm clean\\n```\\n### Git Workflow and Commit Conventions\\n\\nWe use **Conventional Commits**  for clear, machine-readable commit messages:\\n\\n```\\ntype(scope): brief description\\n\\nOptional longer explanation of the change and why it was made.\\n```\\n**Commit Types:**\\n\\n- `feat:` - New feature or functionality\\n\\n- `fix:` - Bug fix\\n\\n- `docs:` - Documentation changes (no code changes)\\n\\n- `style:` - Code style changes (formatting, semicolons, etc.)\\n\\n- `refactor:` - Code changes without new features or fixes\\n\\n- `test:` - Test additions or modifications\\n\\n- `chore:` - Dependency updates, tooling, etc.\\n\\n**Example Commits:**\\n\\n```\\nfeat(core): add Result type for error handling\\nfix(types): correct generic constraints on Handler interface\\ndocs: update AGENTS.md with architecture overview\\nrefactor(core): simplify validation logic\\ntest(core): add tests for Result type\\n```\\n## Key Concepts\\n\\n### Result<T, E> Pattern\\n\\nWe use a Result type (similar to Rust) for explicit error handling:\\n\\n```\\ntype Result<T, E> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: E };\\n```\\nThis provides:\\n\\n- **Explicit error handling**  - No surprise errors\\n\\n- **Type-safe operations**  - Compiler enforces error handling\\n\\n- **Clear intent**  - Functions signal they may fail\\n\\n- **Composability**  - Easy to chain operations\\n\\n### TypeScript Project References\\n\\nWe use `tsconfig.json` project references for:\\n\\n- **Proper compilation order**  - Dependencies compile first\\n\\n- **Incremental builds**  - Only rebuild what changed\\n\\n- **Dependency validation**  - Prevent circular dependencies\\n\\n- **Clear boundaries**  - Explicit package dependencies\\n\\nConfiguration example:\\n\\n```\\n{\\n \\\"references\\\": [{ \\\"path\\\": \\\"./packages/types\\\" }, { \\\"path\\\": \\\"./packages/core\\\" }]\\n}\\n```\\n### Unified Knowledge Graph\\n\\nThe `packages/graph` package provides a graph-based context system that unifies code structure, organizational knowledge, and external data into a single queryable model. It powers context assembly, entropy detection, constraint enforcement, and skill execution across the entire toolkit. Key components: LokiJS graph store, ContextQL query engine, FusionLayer (keyword + semantic search), code/git/knowledge ingestion pipelines, and 4 external connectors (Jira, Slack, Confluence, CI).\\n\\n### Community Skill Registry\\n\\nThe `@harness-skills/*` npm namespace enables publishing, discovering, and installing community skills. Key commands: `harness install`, `harness uninstall`, `harness skill search`, `harness skill create`, `harness skill publish`. Supports local installs (`--from ./path`), private registries (`--registry <url>`), and `.npmrc` auth tokens. Skills are pure content packages (no runtime code). Discovery priority: project-local > community > bundled.\\n\\nImplementation in `packages/cli/src/registry/` and `packages/cli/src/commands/skill/`. See the  for full usage, architecture, and examples.\\n\\n### Project Roadmap\\n\\nThe project roadmap lives at `docs/roadmap.md` and tracks features across milestones with statuses (`backlog`, `planned`, `in-progress`, `done`, `blocked`). Core implementation in `packages/core/src/roadmap/` provides `parseRoadmap`, `serializeRoadmap`, and `syncRoadmap`. The `manage_roadmap` MCP tool (`packages/cli/src/mcp/tools/roadmap.ts`) exposes CRUD operations: `show`, `add`, `update`, `remove`, `query`, `sync`. The `harness-roadmap` skill provides interactive workflows: `--create`, `--add`, `--sync`, `--edit`, `--query`. Roadmap sync respects a \\\"human-always-wins\\\" rule — manually edited statuses are preserved unless `force_sync` is set. The orchestrator adapter (`packages/orchestrator/src/tracker/adapters/roadmap.ts`) maps roadmap features to the internal Issue model for agent orchestration.\\n\\n### Monorepo Structure Benefits\\n\\n- **Shared Dependencies**  - One pnpm-lock.yaml ensures consistency\\n\\n- **Unified Tooling**  - Same linting, formatting, and test configuration\\n\\n- **Coordinated Changes**  - Easy to update multiple packages together\\n\\n- **Turborepo Caching**  - Faster builds with smart caching\\n\\n### Documentation-First Approach\\n\\nAll architectural decisions must be documented:\\n\\n1. **Design Documents**  - Explain the \\\"why\\\" before implementing\\n\\n2. **Architecture Decisions**  - Record key choices in `/docs/standard/`\\n\\n3. **Implementation Plans**  - Track execution in `/docs/plans/`\\n\\n4. **Specifications**  - Detailed technical specs in `/docs/changes/`\\n\\n5. **Guides**  - How-to documentation for common tasks\\n\\nThis creates a permanent record that AI agents can access and understand.\\n\\n## Where to Find Things\\n\\n### Documentation Structure\\n\\n-   - Core Harness Engineering standard and principles\\n\\n    - `index.md` - Overview of the standard\\n\\n    - `principles.md` - Deep dive into the 7 core principles\\n\\n    - `implementation.md` - Step-by-step adoption guide\\n\\n    - `kpis.md` - Metrics for measuring success\\n\\n-   - How-to guides and tutorials\\n\\n    - `getting-started.md` - Quick start guide for new projects\\n\\n    - `best-practices.md` - Recommended patterns and practices\\n\\n    - Additional guides for specific topics\\n\\n-   - Technical reference documentation\\n\\n    - Configuration reference\\n\\n    - CLI documentation\\n\\n    - API reference\\n\\n-   - API documentation (placeholder — currently contains only index.md)\\n\\n-   - Detailed technical specifications for features\\n\\n-   - Implementation and execution plans\\n\\n### Key Documentation\\n\\nWhen working on this project, agents should prioritize reading:\\n\\n1. **First** :  - Understanding the vision\\n\\n2. **Second** :  - Understanding how it works\\n\\n3. **Third** :  - Practical setup\\n\\n4. **Reference** :  - Detailed guidance\\n\\n5. **Context** : This file (AGENTS.md) - Navigation and quick reference\\n\\n## Conventions\\n\\n### Code Style\\n\\n- **TypeScript Strict Mode**  - All code compiles with `strict: true`\\n\\n- **ESLint**  - Configured in `eslint.config.js` for code quality rules\\n\\n- **Prettier**  - Auto-formatting with rules in `.prettierrc.json`\\n\\n    - 2-space indentation\\n\\n    - Single quotes for strings\\n\\n    - Trailing commas where valid\\n\\n    - Line length: 100 characters (practical limit)\\n\\n### Code Organization\\n\\n- **Barrel Exports**  - Each package has `src/index.ts` that re-exports public API\\n\\n- **Type-Safe Code**  - No `any` types unless absolutely necessary with `// @ts-ignore` comments\\n\\n- **Clear Imports**  - Explicit imports from package exports, not internal paths\\n\\n### Commit Message Format\\n\\nFollow **Conventional Commits**  (see Git Workflow section above):\\n\\n```\\ntype(scope): brief description under 50 chars\\n\\nOptional longer body explaining the \\\"why\\\" and \\\"what\\\" of the change.\\nKeep lines under 72 characters for readability.\\n\\nCloses #123 # Optional reference to related issues\\n```\\n### Documentation Standards\\n\\nWhen writing documentation:\\n\\n1. **Be Specific**  - Explain decisions, not just facts\\n\\n2. **Include Examples**  - Code examples for technical decisions\\n\\n3. **Link References**  - Link to related docs\\n\\n4. **Update AGENTS.md**  - Add new docs to the navigation\\n\\n5. **Explain the Why**  - Focus on reasoning, not just implementation\\n\\nExample documentation template:\\n\\n```\\n# Feature Name\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nOne-sentence description of what this is and why it exists.\\n\\n## Design\\n\\nDetailed explanation of the design and key decisions.\\n\\n## Implementation\\n\\nHow it works technically with code examples.\\n\\n## Examples\\n\\nReal-world usage examples.\\n\\n## Related\\n\\nLinks to related documentation.\\n```\\n### Testing Approach\\n\\n- **Unit Tests**  - Test individual functions and classes\\n\\n- **Integration Tests**  - Test package interactions\\n\\n- **Test Coverage**  - Aim for high coverage of critical paths\\n\\n- **Descriptive Names**  - Test names explain what is being tested\\n\\nTest file locations:\\n\\n- Core code: `src/module.ts`\\n\\n- Tests: `tests/module.test.ts`\\n\\n## Common Tasks for Agents\\n\\n### Adding a New Package\\n\\n1. **Create directory structure** :\\n```\\nmkdir -p packages/my-package/src\\n```\\n\\n2. **Create package.json**  with name `@harness-engineering/my-package`\\n\\n3. **Add TypeScript configuration**  (`tsconfig.json`)\\n\\n4. **Export from src/index.ts**  (barrel export)\\n\\n5. **Add to root tsconfig.json**  references\\n\\n6. **Add to pnpm-workspace.yaml**  if not auto-detected\\n\\n### Updating Documentation\\n\\n1. **Create or edit markdown file**  in appropriate `/docs/` subdirectory\\n\\n2. **Follow documentation standards**  (see Conventions section)\\n\\n3. **Update navigation**  - Add links to AGENTS.md or VitePress config if needed\\n\\n4. **Link to related docs**  - Help agents navigate to context\\n\\n5. **Update AGENTS.md**  if creating new major sections\\n\\n### Running Tests\\n\\n```\\n# Run all tests\\npnpm test\\n\\n# Watch mode for development\\npnpm test:watch\\n\\n# Test specific package\\npnpm test --filter=@harness-engineering/core\\n\\n# Run with coverage\\npnpm test -- --coverage\\n```\\n### Building the Project\\n\\n```\\n# Build all packages\\npnpm build\\n\\n# Build specific package\\npnpm build --filter=@harness-engineering/core\\n\\n# Development mode (watch)\\npnpm dev\\n\\n# Clean build (remove artifacts)\\npnpm clean && pnpm build\\n```\\n## Context for AI Agents\\n\\n### Our Approach to AI Development\\n\\nThis project is **specifically designed**  for AI agents to work on it effectively:\\n\\n1. **Documentation is Law**  - Decisions are recorded, not assumed\\n\\n\"\n}"}],"details":{"url":"https://github.com/Intense-Visions/harness-engineering/blob/main/AGENTS.md","content":"/ Public\n\n- \n\n- \n\n- \n\n- \n\n- \n\n- \n\n## FilesExpand file tree\n\nmain\n\n## Breadcrumbs\n\n1. \n\n/\n\n# AGENTS.md\n\nCopy path\n\n590 lines (412 loc) · 20.7 KB\n\n1. \n\n/\n\n# AGENTS.md\n\n590 lines (412 loc) · 20.7 KB\n\n# Harness Engineering: AI Agent Knowledge Map\n\nThis is the single source of truth for AI agents working on the Harness Engineering project. It provides essential context about our repository structure, architecture, conventions, and where to find information.\n\n## Project Overview\n\n**Harness Engineering**  is a comprehensive toolkit for transitioning from manual coding to **agent-first development** . We help teams architect software in ways that enable AI agents to execute, maintain, and improve code reliably and autonomously.\n\n### Purpose and Goals\n\n- Create a reusable library and toolkit for agent-first development\n\n- Establish patterns that make AI-driven development predictable and scalable\n\n- Document architectural decisions as the single source of truth\n\n- Enforce constraints mechanically rather than through code review\n\n- Measure and improve agent autonomy over time\n\n### Current Phase\n\n**Complete**  — All core packages (types, core, cli, eslint-plugin, linter-gen, graph, orchestrator), 49 skills (claude-code) / 49 skills (gemini-cli), 12 personas, 6 templates, and 3 progressive examples are implemented. The project is in adoption and refinement mode. See `examples/` for progressive tutorials.\n\n## Repository Structure\n\nThis is a **monorepo**  using pnpm workspaces and Turborepo for orchestration.\n\n```\nharness-engineering/\n├── packages/ # Core application packages\n│ ├── types/ # Shared TypeScript types and interfaces\n│ ├── core/ # Core runtime library and utilities\n│ ├── cli/ # CLI tool (harness validate, check-deps, skill, state, etc.)\n│ ├── eslint-plugin/ # ESLint rules for constraint enforcement\n│ ├── linter-gen/ # YAML-to-ESLint rule generator\n│ ├── graph/ # Unified Knowledge Graph: LokiJS store, ContextQL queries, code/git/knowledge ingestion, FusionLayer search, 4 external connectors (Jira, Slack, Confluence, CI)\n│ └── orchestrator/ # Agent orchestration daemon for dispatching coding agents to issues\n├── agents/ # Agent configuration\n│ ├── skills/claude-code/ # 49 skills (skill.yaml + SKILL.md each)\n│ ├── skills/gemini-cli/ # 49 skills (adapted for Gemini CLI, includes sensitive-data-compliance)\n│ └── personas/ # 12 personas (architecture-enforcer, code-reviewer, codebase-health-analyst, documentation-maintainer, entropy-cleaner, graph-maintainer, parallel-coordinator, performance-guardian, planner, security-reviewer, task-executor, verifier)\n├── templates/ # Project scaffolding templates (base, basic, intermediate, advanced, nextjs, orchestrator)\n├── examples/ # Progressive tutorial examples\n│ ├── hello-world/ # Basic adoption level\n│ ├── task-api/ # Intermediate adoption level\n│ └── multi-tenant-api/ # Advanced adoption level\n├── docs/ # Complete documentation suite\n│ ├── standard/ # Harness Engineering principles and standard\n│ ├── guides/ # How-to guides and tutorials\n│ ├── reference/ # Configuration and API reference\n│ ├── specs/ # Detailed technical specifications\n│ ├── plans/ # Implementation and execution plans\n│ ├── research/ # Framework research and analysis\n│ ├── conventions/ # Format conventions (markdown interaction patterns)\n│ └── changes/ # Design change proposals and deltas\n├── package.json # Root package metadata and scripts\n├── tsconfig.json # Root TypeScript configuration\n├── pnpm-workspace.yaml # pnpm workspace definition\n├── turbo.json # Turborepo configuration\n└── AGENTS.md # This file - AI agent knowledge map\n```\n### Package Relationships\n\n- **types**  → Shared type definitions (no dependencies)\n\n- **core**  → Runtime library (depends on types)\n\n- **graph**  → Knowledge graph for codebase relationships and entropy detection (depends on types)\n\n- **orchestrator**  → Agent orchestration and multi-agent coordination (depends on core)\n\n- All packages follow strict dependency rules: no circular dependencies, no upward dependencies\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Layered Architecture\n\nWe follow a strict, one-way dependency model:\n\n```\nTypes (bottom layer - no dependencies)\n ↓\nConfiguration & Constants\n ↓\nRepository & Data Access\n ↓\nServices & Business Logic\n ↓\nAgents & External Interfaces (top layer)\n```\n**Key Rule** : Layers can only depend on lower layers, never upward.\n\n### Design Decisions\n\n1. **TypeScript Strict Mode**  - All code runs with strict type checking enabled\n\n2. **Project References**  - We use tsconfig project references for proper compilation order and dependency validation\n\n3. **Monorepo Structure**  - Enables shared code and consistent tooling across packages\n\n4. **Documentation-First**  - All architectural decisions live in git as version-controlled markdown\n\n5. **Result<T, E> Pattern**  - Explicit error handling using Result types (similar to Rust's Result)\n\n### Module Boundaries\n\nEach package has a clear responsibility:\n\n- **types** : Type definitions, interfaces, and constants used across packages\n\n- **core** : Runtime library with validation, utilities, and common functionality\n\n- See package.json files in each package for full dependency details.\n\n## Development Workflow\n\n### Prerequisites\n\nEnsure you have these tools installed:\n\n- **Node.js 22+**  - Download from \n\n- **pnpm 8+**  - Install with: `npm install -g pnpm`\n\n- **Git**  - Required for version control\n\nVerify your setup:\n\n```\nnode --version # Should be 22.x or higher\npnpm --version # Should be 8.x or higher\ngit --version # Any recent version\n```\n### Setting Up the Project\n\n```\n# 1. Clone the repository\ngit clone https://github.com/Intense-Visions/harness-engineering.git\ncd harness-engineering\n\n# 2. Install all dependencies\npnpm install\n\n# 3. Verify the setup by building\npnpm build\n\n# 4. Run tests to ensure everything works\npnpm test\n```\n### Common Development Tasks\n\n```\n# Install dependencies\npnpm install\n\n# Build all packages\npnpm build\n\n# Watch mode for development\npnpm dev\n\n# Run all tests\npnpm test\n\n# Run tests in watch mode\npnpm test:watch\n\n# Run tests for a specific package\npnpm test --filter=@harness-engineering/core\n\n# Lint all code\npnpm lint\n\n# Format code (TypeScript, JavaScript, Markdown, JSON)\npnpm format\n\n# Check formatting without making changes\npnpm format:check\n\n# Type checking\npnpm typecheck\n\n# Start documentation server\npnpm docs:dev\n\n# Build documentation\npnpm docs:build\n\n# Preview built documentation\npnpm docs:preview\n\n# Clean build artifacts\npnpm clean\n```\n### Git Workflow and Commit Conventions\n\nWe use **Conventional Commits**  for clear, machine-readable commit messages:\n\n```\ntype(scope): brief description\n\nOptional longer explanation of the change and why it was made.\n```\n**Commit Types:**\n\n- `feat:` - New feature or functionality\n\n- `fix:` - Bug fix\n\n- `docs:` - Documentation changes (no code changes)\n\n- `style:` - Code style changes (formatting, semicolons, etc.)\n\n- `refactor:` - Code changes without new features or fixes\n\n- `test:` - Test additions or modifications\n\n- `chore:` - Dependency updates, tooling, etc.\n\n**Example Commits:**\n\n```\nfeat(core): add Result type for error handling\nfix(types): correct generic constraints on Handler interface\ndocs: update AGENTS.md with architecture overview\nrefactor(core): simplify validation logic\ntest(core): add tests for Result type\n```\n## Key Concepts\n\n### Result<T, E> Pattern\n\nWe use a Result type (similar to Rust) for explicit error handling:\n\n```\ntype Result<T, E> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: E };\n```\nThis provides:\n\n- **Explicit error handling**  - No surprise errors\n\n- **Type-safe operations**  - Compiler enforces error handling\n\n- **Clear intent**  - Functions signal they may fail\n\n- **Composability**  - Easy to chain operations\n\n### TypeScript Project References\n\nWe use `tsconfig.json` project references for:\n\n- **Proper compilation order**  - Dependencies compile first\n\n- **Incremental builds**  - Only rebuild what changed\n\n- **Dependency validation**  - Prevent circular dependencies\n\n- **Clear boundaries**  - Explicit package dependencies\n\nConfiguration example:\n\n```\n{\n \"references\": [{ \"path\": \"./packages/types\" }, { \"path\": \"./packages/core\" }]\n}\n```\n### Unified Knowledge Graph\n\nThe `packages/graph` package provides a graph-based context system that unifies code structure, organizational knowledge, and external data into a single queryable model. It powers context assembly, entropy detection, constraint enforcement, and skill execution across the entire toolkit. Key components: LokiJS graph store, ContextQL query engine, FusionLayer (keyword + semantic search), code/git/knowledge ingestion pipelines, and 4 external connectors (Jira, Slack, Confluence, CI).\n\n### Community Skill Registry\n\nThe `@harness-skills/*` npm namespace enables publishing, discovering, and installing community skills. Key commands: `harness install`, `harness uninstall`, `harness skill search`, `harness skill create`, `harness skill publish`. Supports local installs (`--from ./path`), private registries (`--registry <url>`), and `.npmrc` auth tokens. Skills are pure content packages (no runtime code). Discovery priority: project-local > community > bundled.\n\nImplementation in `packages/cli/src/registry/` and `packages/cli/src/commands/skill/`. See the  for full usage, architecture, and examples.\n\n### Project Roadmap\n\nThe project roadmap lives at `docs/roadmap.md` and tracks features across milestones with statuses (`backlog`, `planned`, `in-progress`, `done`, `blocked`). Core implementation in `packages/core/src/roadmap/` provides `parseRoadmap`, `serializeRoadmap`, and `syncRoadmap`. The `manage_roadmap` MCP tool (`packages/cli/src/mcp/tools/roadmap.ts`) exposes CRUD operations: `show`, `add`, `update`, `remove`, `query`, `sync`. The `harness-roadmap` skill provides interactive workflows: `--create`, `--add`, `--sync`, `--edit`, `--query`. Roadmap sync respects a \"human-always-wins\" rule — manually edited statuses are preserved unless `force_sync` is set. The orchestrator adapter (`packages/orchestrator/src/tracker/adapters/roadmap.ts`) maps roadmap features to the internal Issue model for agent orchestration.\n\n### Monorepo Structure Benefits\n\n- **Shared Dependencies**  - One pnpm-lock.yaml ensures consistency\n\n- **Unified Tooling**  - Same linting, formatting, and test configuration\n\n- **Coordinated Changes**  - Easy to update multiple packages together\n\n- **Turborepo Caching**  - Faster builds with smart caching\n\n### Documentation-First Approach\n\nAll architectural decisions must be documented:\n\n1. **Design Documents**  - Explain the \"why\" before implementing\n\n2. **Architecture Decisions**  - Record key choices in `/docs/standard/`\n\n3. **Implementation Plans**  - Track execution in `/docs/plans/`\n\n4. **Specifications**  - Detailed technical specs in `/docs/changes/`\n\n5. **Guides**  - How-to documentation for common tasks\n\nThis creates a permanent record that AI agents can access and understand.\n\n## Where to Find Things\n\n### Documentation Structure\n\n-   - Core Harness Engineering standard and principles\n\n    - `index.md` - Overview of the standard\n\n    - `principles.md` - Deep dive into the 7 core principles\n\n    - `implementation.md` - Step-by-step adoption guide\n\n    - `kpis.md` - Metrics for measuring success\n\n-   - How-to guides and tutorials\n\n    - `getting-started.md` - Quick start guide for new projects\n\n    - `best-practices.md` - Recommended patterns and practices\n\n    - Additional guides for specific topics\n\n-   - Technical reference documentation\n\n    - Configuration reference\n\n    - CLI documentation\n\n    - API reference\n\n-   - API documentation (placeholder — currently contains only index.md)\n\n-   - Detailed technical specifications for features\n\n-   - Implementation and execution plans\n\n### Key Documentation\n\nWhen working on this project, agents should prioritize reading:\n\n1. **First** :  - Understanding the vision\n\n2. **Second** :  - Understanding how it works\n\n3. **Third** :  - Practical setup\n\n4. **Reference** :  - Detailed guidance\n\n5. **Context** : This file (AGENTS.md) - Navigation and quick reference\n\n## Conventions\n\n### Code Style\n\n- **TypeScript Strict Mode**  - All code compiles with `strict: true`\n\n- **ESLint**  - Configured in `eslint.config.js` for code quality rules\n\n- **Prettier**  - Auto-formatting with rules in `.prettierrc.json`\n\n    - 2-space indentation\n\n    - Single quotes for strings\n\n    - Trailing commas where valid\n\n    - Line length: 100 characters (practical limit)\n\n### Code Organization\n\n- **Barrel Exports**  - Each package has `src/index.ts` that re-exports public API\n\n- **Type-Safe Code**  - No `any` types unless absolutely necessary with `// @ts-ignore` comments\n\n- **Clear Imports**  - Explicit imports from package exports, not internal paths\n\n### Commit Message Format\n\nFollow **Conventional Commits**  (see Git Workflow section above):\n\n```\ntype(scope): brief description under 50 chars\n\nOptional longer body explaining the \"why\" and \"what\" of the change.\nKeep lines under 72 characters for readability.\n\nCloses #123 # Optional reference to related issues\n```\n### Documentation Standards\n\nWhen writing documentation:\n\n1. **Be Specific**  - Explain decisions, not just facts\n\n2. **Include Examples**  - Code examples for technical decisions\n\n3. **Link References**  - Link to related docs\n\n4. **Update AGENTS.md**  - Add new docs to the navigation\n\n5. **Explain the Why**  - Focus on reasoning, not just implementation\n\nExample documentation template:\n\n```\n# Feature Name\n\n## Overview\n\nOne-sentence description of what this is and why it exists.\n\n## Design\n\nDetailed explanation of the design and key decisions.\n\n## Implementation\n\nHow it works technically with code examples.\n\n## Examples\n\nReal-world usage examples.\n\n## Related\n\nLinks to related documentation.\n```\n### Testing Approach\n\n- **Unit Tests**  - Test individual functions and classes\n\n- **Integration Tests**  - Test package interactions\n\n- **Test Coverage**  - Aim for high coverage of critical paths\n\n- **Descriptive Names**  - Test names explain what is being tested\n\nTest file locations:\n\n- Core code: `src/module.ts`\n\n- Tests: `tests/module.test.ts`\n\n## Common Tasks for Agents\n\n### Adding a New Package\n\n1. **Create directory structure** :\n```\nmkdir -p packages/my-package/src\n```\n\n2. **Create package.json**  with name `@harness-engineering/my-package`\n\n3. **Add TypeScript configuration**  (`tsconfig.json`)\n\n4. **Export from src/index.ts**  (barrel export)\n\n5. **Add to root tsconfig.json**  references\n\n6. **Add to pnpm-workspace.yaml**  if not auto-detected\n\n### Updating Documentation\n\n1. **Create or edit markdown file**  in appropriate `/docs/` subdirectory\n\n2. **Follow documentation standards**  (see Conventions section)\n\n3. **Update navigation**  - Add links to AGENTS.md or VitePress config if needed\n\n4. **Link to related docs**  - Help agents navigate to context\n\n5. **Update AGENTS.md**  if creating new major sections\n\n### Running Tests\n\n```\n# Run all tests\npnpm test\n\n# Watch mode for development\npnpm test:watch\n\n# Test specific package\npnpm test --filter=@harness-engineering/core\n\n# Run with coverage\npnpm test -- --coverage\n```\n### Building the Project\n\n```\n# Build all packages\npnpm build\n\n# Build specific package\npnpm build --filter=@harness-engineering/core\n\n# Development mode (watch)\npnpm dev\n\n# Clean build (remove artifacts)\npnpm clean && pnpm build\n```\n## Context for AI Agents\n\n### Our Approach to AI Development\n\nThis project is **specifically designed**  for AI agents to work on it effectively:\n\n1. **Documentation is Law**  - Decisions are recorded, not assumed\n\n"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800873245}}
{"type":"message","id":"59ebf5ec","parentId":"303da8c2","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:01:24.101Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, I got a lot of content. Let me also fetch the best practices gist and the main README to get a more complete picture of harness engineering.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wb2fnunuppx9_1","name":"web_crawl","arguments":{"url":"https://gist.github.com/celesteanders/21edad2367c8ede2ff092bd87e56a26f"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":7077,"output":85,"cacheRead":32251,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39413,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775800873247,"responseId":"chatcmpl-742a214e-d54b-49dd-8f75-55cce05aa36f"}}
{"type":"message","id":"afe90c5c","parentId":"59ebf5ec","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:01:24.436Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_wb2fnunuppx9_1","toolName":"web_crawl","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"url\": \"https://gist.github.com/celesteanders/21edad2367c8ede2ff092bd87e56a26f\",\n  \"content\": \"\\n\\n# /\\n\\n Created  April 2, 2026 01:33\\n\\n  \\n\\n Harness Engineering Best Practices from Anthropic and OpenAI  \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n# Best Practices for Building an Agent Harness\\n\\nConsolidated from Anthropic, OpenAI, and community research on autonomous coding agent harnesses.\\n\\n## 1. Architecture\\n\\n### Use a multi-agent pattern with separated concerns\\n\\nSplit work across specialized agents rather than overloading a single agent. Common roles:\\n\\n- **Planner**  -- Expands a short prompt into a full product/feature spec. Focus on product context and high-level technical design, not granular implementation details. Over-specifying upfront causes cascading errors downstream.\\n\\n- **Generator/Builder**  -- Implements features one at a time against the spec. Works in focused increments.\\n\\n- **Evaluator/QA**  -- Tests the running application as a user would, grades output against criteria, and sends concrete feedback back to the generator for iteration.\\n\\nThe evaluator is critical because agents consistently rate their own work too generously. Separating generation from evaluation creates an honest feedback loop. Tuning a standalone evaluator to be skeptical is far more tractable than making a generator critical of its own work.\\n\\n### Keep it monolithic until complexity demands otherwise\\n\\nStart with a single-agent loop before reaching for multi-agent orchestration. Multi-agent systems introduce the same complexity as microservices, compounded by non-determinism. Only add agents when you hit a specific ceiling that a single agent cannot overcome.\\n\\n### Fresh context windows per session (context resets)\\n\\nCreate a new client/context for each session rather than relying on compaction alone. Compaction preserves continuity but doesn't eliminate \\\"context anxiety\\\" (agents wrapping up prematurely as context fills). A full reset gives a clean slate, with structured handoff artifacts bridging the gap.\\n\\nNote: More capable models (e.g., Opus 4.6) may handle long contexts well enough that compaction suffices and context resets become optional. Re-evaluate this as models improve.\\n\\n## 2. State Management and Persistence\\n\\n### Persist state in structured files, not in context\\n\\nThe agent's context window is ephemeral. Everything that must survive between sessions needs to be written to disk:\\n\\n- **Task/feature list**  (JSON, not Markdown) -- The single source of truth for what's done and what's remaining. JSON resists model-induced corruption better than freeform Markdown. Rules: never remove or reorder items, only flip status from incomplete to complete.\\n\\n- **Progress notes**  (free-form text) -- What was accomplished, bugs found/fixed, what to work on next, architectural decisions. Written at the end of each session.\\n\\n- **Plan/spec file**  -- The original requirements. Kept in the project directory so the agent can reference it.\\n\\n- **Init/setup script**  -- Automates environment setup so the agent doesn't waste context on installation.\\n\\n- **Git history**  -- Descriptive commits act as a recovery mechanism. The agent reads recent commits at session start to understand what changed.\\n\\n### Use the repository as the system of record\\n\\nAnything the agent can't access in-context effectively doesn't exist. Push all relevant knowledge into the repo: decisions from Slack threads, architectural patterns, product context. If it's not discoverable by the agent, it's illegible.\\n\\n### AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md should be a map, not an encyclopedia\\n\\nKeep the top-level instruction file short (\\\\~100 lines). Use it as a table of contents pointing to deeper sources of truth in a structured `docs/` directory. A giant instruction file crowds out the task and rots quickly.\\n\\nStructure knowledge for progressive disclosure: agents start with a small, stable entry point and are taught where to look, rather than being overwhelmed up front.\\n\\n## 3. The Session Protocol\\n\\n### Follow a consistent session lifecycle\\n\\nEvery session should follow a predictable sequence:\\n\\n1. **Orient**  -- Read progress notes, task list, recent git history\\n\\n2. **Setup**  -- Run init script to start dev servers / prerequisites\\n\\n3. **Verify baseline**  -- Test that existing functionality still works before touching anything new. The previous session may have introduced bugs.\\n\\n4. **Select one task**  -- Pick the highest-priority incomplete item\\n\\n5. **Implement**  -- Build the feature\\n\\n6. **Test**  -- Verify through the actual UI/API, not just unit tests\\n\\n7. **Update state**  -- Mark task complete, commit with descriptive message, write progress notes\\n\\n8. **Clean exit**  -- Confirm the application is in a working state\\n\\n### One task per session\\n\\nThis prevents context exhaustion and keeps each session focused and recoverable. You may relax this as the project matures and the agent demonstrates reliability, but tighten it back if quality degrades.\\n\\n### Verify before building\\n\\nAlways run baseline verification at the start of a session. Compounding bugs across sessions is one of the most common failure modes.\\n\\n## 4. Feedback Loops and Backpressure\\n\\n### Wire in automated verification as backpressure\\n\\nAnything that can reject invalid output should be part of the loop: type checkers, linters, test suites, static analyzers, security scanners. The key constraint: the feedback wheel must turn fast. Slow verification (e.g., long compile times) reduces the number of iterations the agent can attempt.\\n\\nAfter implementing functionality, immediately run tests for that specific unit of code.\\n\\n### Use browser/UI automation for verification\\n\\nAgents will mark features complete without actually testing them unless forced to interact with the running application. Use tools like Puppeteer or Playwright MCP to navigate, click, fill forms, and take screenshots. This catches bugs that backend-only testing misses.\\n\\n### Build an evaluator with concrete grading criteria\\n\\nDon't ask \\\"is this good?\\\" -- define specific, gradable criteria. For each criterion, provide:\\n\\n- A clear definition of what good looks like\\n\\n- Few-shot examples with score breakdowns for calibration\\n\\n- Hard thresholds that trigger a failing grade\\n\\nWeight criteria toward areas where the model is weakest (e.g., design originality, feature completeness) rather than areas it handles well by default (e.g., basic functionality, code correctness).\\n\\n### Use sprint contracts for complex work\\n\\nBefore each implementation chunk, have the generator and evaluator negotiate what \\\"done\\\" looks like. The generator proposes what it will build and how success is verified; the evaluator reviews the proposal. This bridges the gap between high-level specs and testable implementation.\\n\\n## 5. Context Window Management\\n\\n### Treat context as a scarce resource\\n\\nThe more context you consume, the worse the outcomes. Strategies:\\n\\n- **Offload expensive work to subagents**  -- The primary context window should operate as a scheduler. Spawn subagents for file system searches, code analysis, test execution, and summarization.\\n\\n- **Deterministically load the same core files each loop**  -- Your plan and specifications should be loaded every iteration so the agent always has the same foundation.\\n\\n- **Don't assume code doesn't exist**  -- Code search (ripgrep) is non-deterministic. Instruct the agent to search before implementing to avoid duplicate implementations.\\n\\n### Use subagents strategically\\n\\n- Fan out subagents for read-only operations (search, analysis) with high parallelism\\n\\n- Limit parallelism for write operations (build, test) to avoid backpressure issues\\n\\n- Use subagents to summarize results rather than dumping raw output into the primary context\\n\\n## 6. Prompt Engineering for Harnesses\\n\\n### Prevent placeholder implementations\\n\\nAgents are biased toward minimal/stub implementations because compiling code triggers their reward function. Explicitly instruct against placeholders and enforce full implementations. Use strong language if needed.\\n\\n### Instruct agents to document their reasoning\\n\\nWhen writing tests or making architectural decisions, have the agent capture the \\\"why\\\" in documentation or comments. Future iterations won't have the original reasoning in their context window, so these notes help the agent decide whether to keep, modify, or remove code.\\n\\n### Allow the agent to self-improve its instructions\\n\\nPermit the agent to update AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md with learnings about how to build, test, and run the project. If the agent runs a command multiple times before finding the correct one, it should update the instructions so future loops don't repeat the mistake.\\n\\n### Capture bugs immediately\\n\\nWhen the agent discovers a bug (even unrelated to current work), it should document it in the plan/todo file immediately, then fix it or leave it for a future loop.\\n\\n## 7. Security and Sandboxing\\n\\n### Defense in depth with three layers\\n\\n1. **OS-level sandbox**  -- Isolate the agent's execution environment\\n\\n2. **Filesystem restrictions**  -- Limit file operations to the project directory\\n\\n3. **Command allowlist**  -- Only permit commands the agent needs. Parse commands with `shlex`, handle pipes/chaining, and block anything not explicitly allowed. Add validation for sensitive commands (e.g., `pkill` only for dev processes, `chmod` only for `+x`).\\n\\n## 8. Code Quality and Architecture\\n\\n### Enforce invariants mechanically, not through documentation alone\\n\\nUse linters, structural tests, and CI checks to enforce architectural rules. Custom lint error messages should include remediation instructions so the agent can fix issues without human intervention.\\n\\nWrite lint rules as code so they apply everywhere at once. In an agent-generated codebase, encoded rules become multipliers.\\n\\n### Treat technical debt like garbage collection\\n\\nRun recurring cleanup agents that scan for deviations from \\\"golden principles,\\\" update quality grades, and open targeted refactoring PRs. Pay down debt continuously in small increments rather than letting it compound.\\n\\n### Optimize for agent legibility, not just human readability\\n\\nStructure the codebase so agents can reason about the full business domain from the repository itself. Favor \\\"boring\\\" technologies (composable, stable APIs, well-represented in training data) over cutting-edge ones that are harder for agents to model.\\n\\n### Make the application inspectable by agents\\n\\n- Boot the app per git worktree so agents can run isolated instances\\n\\n- Wire browser DevTools protocol into the agent runtime for DOM snapshots and screenshots\\n\\n- Expose logs, metrics, and traces via queryable APIs (LogQL, PromQL) in ephemeral observability stacks\\n\\n## 9. Recovery and Resilience\\n\\n### Git is your safety net\\n\\n- Commit after every successful task with descriptive messages\\n\\n- Read recent git history at the start of each session\\n\\n- Use git tags to mark known-good states\\n\\n- When the agent produces a broken codebase, `git reset --hard` to the last good state and re-run\\n\\n### Expect failures and plan for them\\n\\nYou will wake up to broken builds. The question is always: is it easier to reset and re-run, or to craft prompts to rescue the current state? Both are valid strategies.\\n\\n### Regenerate the plan periodically\\n\\nTodo lists and plans drift over time. Periodically delete and regenerate them by having the agent compare the current codebase against the specification. This prevents the agent from following stale or incorrect plans.\\n\\n## 10. Evolving the Harness\\n\\n### Re-evaluate harness complexity with each model upgrade\\n\\nEvery component in a harness encodes an assumption about what the model can't do on its own. These assumptions go stale as models improve. When a new model lands:\\n\\n- Strip away scaffolding that's no longer load-bearing\\n\\n- Add new components to achieve capabilities that weren't possible before\\n\\n- Test by removing one component at a time and reviewing the impact\\n\\n### The evaluator's value depends on task difficulty\\n\\nThe evaluator adds the most value when the task sits at or beyond the edge of what the generator can handle solo. For tasks well within the model's capability, it becomes unnecessary overhead. Calibrate accordingly.\\n\\n### Start simple, add complexity only when needed\\n\\nFind the simplest solution possible. Only increase complexity when you hit a specific, demonstrable ceiling. Three similar lines of code are better than a premature abstraction. A single-agent loop is better than a multi-agent system until the single agent provably fails.\\n\\n## References\\n\\n-  -- Anthropic, Nov 2025\\n\\n-  -- Geoffrey Huntley, Jul 2025\\n\\n-  -- Anthropic, Mar 2026\\n\\n-  -- OpenAI, Feb 2026\\n\\n## Summary: The Core Principles\\n\\n1. **Context windows are the constraint; structured artifacts are the solution.**  Everything exists to bridge the gap between sessions.\\n\\n2. **Separate generation from evaluation.**  Agents can't objectively judge their own work.\\n\\n3. **One task per session.**  Focus prevents context exhaustion and keeps sessions recoverable.\\n\\n4. **Verify before building.**  Always check the previous session didn't break things.\\n\\n5. **Wire in fast feedback loops.**  Tests, linters, type checkers, and UI automation as backpressure.\\n\\n6. **Repository is the single source of truth.**  If it's not in the repo, it doesn't exist for the agent.\\n\\n7. **Humans steer, agents execute.**  Engineers design environments, specify intent, and build feedback loops. The agent writes the code.\\n\\n8. **Expect eventual consistency.**  Most issues can be resolved through more loops with better-tuned prompts.\\n\\n9. **Simplify relentlessly.**  Strip harness complexity that the model no longer needs. The interesting work moves, it doesn't shrink.\"\n}"}],"details":{"url":"https://gist.github.com/celesteanders/21edad2367c8ede2ff092bd87e56a26f","content":"\n\n# /\n\n Created  April 2, 2026 01:33\n\n  \n\n Harness Engineering Best Practices from Anthropic and OpenAI  \n\n\n\n\n\n# Best Practices for Building an Agent Harness\n\nConsolidated from Anthropic, OpenAI, and community research on autonomous coding agent harnesses.\n\n## 1. Architecture\n\n### Use a multi-agent pattern with separated concerns\n\nSplit work across specialized agents rather than overloading a single agent. Common roles:\n\n- **Planner**  -- Expands a short prompt into a full product/feature spec. Focus on product context and high-level technical design, not granular implementation details. Over-specifying upfront causes cascading errors downstream.\n\n- **Generator/Builder**  -- Implements features one at a time against the spec. Works in focused increments.\n\n- **Evaluator/QA**  -- Tests the running application as a user would, grades output against criteria, and sends concrete feedback back to the generator for iteration.\n\nThe evaluator is critical because agents consistently rate their own work too generously. Separating generation from evaluation creates an honest feedback loop. Tuning a standalone evaluator to be skeptical is far more tractable than making a generator critical of its own work.\n\n### Keep it monolithic until complexity demands otherwise\n\nStart with a single-agent loop before reaching for multi-agent orchestration. Multi-agent systems introduce the same complexity as microservices, compounded by non-determinism. Only add agents when you hit a specific ceiling that a single agent cannot overcome.\n\n### Fresh context windows per session (context resets)\n\nCreate a new client/context for each session rather than relying on compaction alone. Compaction preserves continuity but doesn't eliminate \"context anxiety\" (agents wrapping up prematurely as context fills). A full reset gives a clean slate, with structured handoff artifacts bridging the gap.\n\nNote: More capable models (e.g., Opus 4.6) may handle long contexts well enough that compaction suffices and context resets become optional. Re-evaluate this as models improve.\n\n## 2. State Management and Persistence\n\n### Persist state in structured files, not in context\n\nThe agent's context window is ephemeral. Everything that must survive between sessions needs to be written to disk:\n\n- **Task/feature list**  (JSON, not Markdown) -- The single source of truth for what's done and what's remaining. JSON resists model-induced corruption better than freeform Markdown. Rules: never remove or reorder items, only flip status from incomplete to complete.\n\n- **Progress notes**  (free-form text) -- What was accomplished, bugs found/fixed, what to work on next, architectural decisions. Written at the end of each session.\n\n- **Plan/spec file**  -- The original requirements. Kept in the project directory so the agent can reference it.\n\n- **Init/setup script**  -- Automates environment setup so the agent doesn't waste context on installation.\n\n- **Git history**  -- Descriptive commits act as a recovery mechanism. The agent reads recent commits at session start to understand what changed.\n\n### Use the repository as the system of record\n\nAnything the agent can't access in-context effectively doesn't exist. Push all relevant knowledge into the repo: decisions from Slack threads, architectural patterns, product context. If it's not discoverable by the agent, it's illegible.\n\n### AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md should be a map, not an encyclopedia\n\nKeep the top-level instruction file short (\\~100 lines). Use it as a table of contents pointing to deeper sources of truth in a structured `docs/` directory. A giant instruction file crowds out the task and rots quickly.\n\nStructure knowledge for progressive disclosure: agents start with a small, stable entry point and are taught where to look, rather than being overwhelmed up front.\n\n## 3. The Session Protocol\n\n### Follow a consistent session lifecycle\n\nEvery session should follow a predictable sequence:\n\n1. **Orient**  -- Read progress notes, task list, recent git history\n\n2. **Setup**  -- Run init script to start dev servers / prerequisites\n\n3. **Verify baseline**  -- Test that existing functionality still works before touching anything new. The previous session may have introduced bugs.\n\n4. **Select one task**  -- Pick the highest-priority incomplete item\n\n5. **Implement**  -- Build the feature\n\n6. **Test**  -- Verify through the actual UI/API, not just unit tests\n\n7. **Update state**  -- Mark task complete, commit with descriptive message, write progress notes\n\n8. **Clean exit**  -- Confirm the application is in a working state\n\n### One task per session\n\nThis prevents context exhaustion and keeps each session focused and recoverable. You may relax this as the project matures and the agent demonstrates reliability, but tighten it back if quality degrades.\n\n### Verify before building\n\nAlways run baseline verification at the start of a session. Compounding bugs across sessions is one of the most common failure modes.\n\n## 4. Feedback Loops and Backpressure\n\n### Wire in automated verification as backpressure\n\nAnything that can reject invalid output should be part of the loop: type checkers, linters, test suites, static analyzers, security scanners. The key constraint: the feedback wheel must turn fast. Slow verification (e.g., long compile times) reduces the number of iterations the agent can attempt.\n\nAfter implementing functionality, immediately run tests for that specific unit of code.\n\n### Use browser/UI automation for verification\n\nAgents will mark features complete without actually testing them unless forced to interact with the running application. Use tools like Puppeteer or Playwright MCP to navigate, click, fill forms, and take screenshots. This catches bugs that backend-only testing misses.\n\n### Build an evaluator with concrete grading criteria\n\nDon't ask \"is this good?\" -- define specific, gradable criteria. For each criterion, provide:\n\n- A clear definition of what good looks like\n\n- Few-shot examples with score breakdowns for calibration\n\n- Hard thresholds that trigger a failing grade\n\nWeight criteria toward areas where the model is weakest (e.g., design originality, feature completeness) rather than areas it handles well by default (e.g., basic functionality, code correctness).\n\n### Use sprint contracts for complex work\n\nBefore each implementation chunk, have the generator and evaluator negotiate what \"done\" looks like. The generator proposes what it will build and how success is verified; the evaluator reviews the proposal. This bridges the gap between high-level specs and testable implementation.\n\n## 5. Context Window Management\n\n### Treat context as a scarce resource\n\nThe more context you consume, the worse the outcomes. Strategies:\n\n- **Offload expensive work to subagents**  -- The primary context window should operate as a scheduler. Spawn subagents for file system searches, code analysis, test execution, and summarization.\n\n- **Deterministically load the same core files each loop**  -- Your plan and specifications should be loaded every iteration so the agent always has the same foundation.\n\n- **Don't assume code doesn't exist**  -- Code search (ripgrep) is non-deterministic. Instruct the agent to search before implementing to avoid duplicate implementations.\n\n### Use subagents strategically\n\n- Fan out subagents for read-only operations (search, analysis) with high parallelism\n\n- Limit parallelism for write operations (build, test) to avoid backpressure issues\n\n- Use subagents to summarize results rather than dumping raw output into the primary context\n\n## 6. Prompt Engineering for Harnesses\n\n### Prevent placeholder implementations\n\nAgents are biased toward minimal/stub implementations because compiling code triggers their reward function. Explicitly instruct against placeholders and enforce full implementations. Use strong language if needed.\n\n### Instruct agents to document their reasoning\n\nWhen writing tests or making architectural decisions, have the agent capture the \"why\" in documentation or comments. Future iterations won't have the original reasoning in their context window, so these notes help the agent decide whether to keep, modify, or remove code.\n\n### Allow the agent to self-improve its instructions\n\nPermit the agent to update AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md with learnings about how to build, test, and run the project. If the agent runs a command multiple times before finding the correct one, it should update the instructions so future loops don't repeat the mistake.\n\n### Capture bugs immediately\n\nWhen the agent discovers a bug (even unrelated to current work), it should document it in the plan/todo file immediately, then fix it or leave it for a future loop.\n\n## 7. Security and Sandboxing\n\n### Defense in depth with three layers\n\n1. **OS-level sandbox**  -- Isolate the agent's execution environment\n\n2. **Filesystem restrictions**  -- Limit file operations to the project directory\n\n3. **Command allowlist**  -- Only permit commands the agent needs. Parse commands with `shlex`, handle pipes/chaining, and block anything not explicitly allowed. Add validation for sensitive commands (e.g., `pkill` only for dev processes, `chmod` only for `+x`).\n\n## 8. Code Quality and Architecture\n\n### Enforce invariants mechanically, not through documentation alone\n\nUse linters, structural tests, and CI checks to enforce architectural rules. Custom lint error messages should include remediation instructions so the agent can fix issues without human intervention.\n\nWrite lint rules as code so they apply everywhere at once. In an agent-generated codebase, encoded rules become multipliers.\n\n### Treat technical debt like garbage collection\n\nRun recurring cleanup agents that scan for deviations from \"golden principles,\" update quality grades, and open targeted refactoring PRs. Pay down debt continuously in small increments rather than letting it compound.\n\n### Optimize for agent legibility, not just human readability\n\nStructure the codebase so agents can reason about the full business domain from the repository itself. Favor \"boring\" technologies (composable, stable APIs, well-represented in training data) over cutting-edge ones that are harder for agents to model.\n\n### Make the application inspectable by agents\n\n- Boot the app per git worktree so agents can run isolated instances\n\n- Wire browser DevTools protocol into the agent runtime for DOM snapshots and screenshots\n\n- Expose logs, metrics, and traces via queryable APIs (LogQL, PromQL) in ephemeral observability stacks\n\n## 9. Recovery and Resilience\n\n### Git is your safety net\n\n- Commit after every successful task with descriptive messages\n\n- Read recent git history at the start of each session\n\n- Use git tags to mark known-good states\n\n- When the agent produces a broken codebase, `git reset --hard` to the last good state and re-run\n\n### Expect failures and plan for them\n\nYou will wake up to broken builds. The question is always: is it easier to reset and re-run, or to craft prompts to rescue the current state? Both are valid strategies.\n\n### Regenerate the plan periodically\n\nTodo lists and plans drift over time. Periodically delete and regenerate them by having the agent compare the current codebase against the specification. This prevents the agent from following stale or incorrect plans.\n\n## 10. Evolving the Harness\n\n### Re-evaluate harness complexity with each model upgrade\n\nEvery component in a harness encodes an assumption about what the model can't do on its own. These assumptions go stale as models improve. When a new model lands:\n\n- Strip away scaffolding that's no longer load-bearing\n\n- Add new components to achieve capabilities that weren't possible before\n\n- Test by removing one component at a time and reviewing the impact\n\n### The evaluator's value depends on task difficulty\n\nThe evaluator adds the most value when the task sits at or beyond the edge of what the generator can handle solo. For tasks well within the model's capability, it becomes unnecessary overhead. Calibrate accordingly.\n\n### Start simple, add complexity only when needed\n\nFind the simplest solution possible. Only increase complexity when you hit a specific, demonstrable ceiling. Three similar lines of code are better than a premature abstraction. A single-agent loop is better than a multi-agent system until the single agent provably fails.\n\n## References\n\n-  -- Anthropic, Nov 2025\n\n-  -- Geoffrey Huntley, Jul 2025\n\n-  -- Anthropic, Mar 2026\n\n-  -- OpenAI, Feb 2026\n\n## Summary: The Core Principles\n\n1. **Context windows are the constraint; structured artifacts are the solution.**  Everything exists to bridge the gap between sessions.\n\n2. **Separate generation from evaluation.**  Agents can't objectively judge their own work.\n\n3. **One task per session.**  Focus prevents context exhaustion and keeps sessions recoverable.\n\n4. **Verify before building.**  Always check the previous session didn't break things.\n\n5. **Wire in fast feedback loops.**  Tests, linters, type checkers, and UI automation as backpressure.\n\n6. **Repository is the single source of truth.**  If it's not in the repo, it doesn't exist for the agent.\n\n7. **Humans steer, agents execute.**  Engineers design environments, specify intent, and build feedback loops. The agent writes the code.\n\n8. **Expect eventual consistency.**  Most issues can be resolved through more loops with better-tuned prompts.\n\n9. **Simplify relentlessly.**  Strip harness complexity that the model no longer needs. The interesting work moves, it doesn't shrink."},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800884435}}
{"type":"message","id":"327813e8","parentId":"afe90c5c","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:01:34.119Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a very comprehensive understanding of Harness Engineering. Let me also check the existing HARNESS_ENGINEERING.md I created yesterday to see what was already covered, and then create an updated comprehensive document based on what I learned from GitHub.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cz4fbckb7x1c_1","name":"read","arguments":{"filePath":"/home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace/HARNESS_ENGINEERING.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":3370,"output":93,"cacheRead":38971,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42434,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775800884437,"responseId":"chatcmpl-02086090-2173-48ff-9004-2770c4e71675"}}
{"type":"message","id":"41dfd421","parentId":"327813e8","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:01:34.131Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_cz4fbckb7x1c_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Harness 工程学习笔记\n\n> 来源：飞书妙记《Harness工程导论》- 李志琦老师  \n> 日期：2026年4月8日\n\n---\n\n## 一、为什么需要 Harness 工程\n\n### Demo 与生产环境的差异\n\n| | Demo 环境 | 生产环境 |\n|---|---|---|\n| 输入 | 可控 | 不可控 |\n| 场景 | 有限 | 无限 |\n| 对抗 | 无 | 有 |\n| 稳定性 | 无要求 | 每次调用都要求正确 |\n| 错误后果 | 无 | 有且成本有约束 |\n\n**关键认知：差距不在模型，而在工程化能力。**\n\nAnthropic 的实验表明：同一个模型，有 Harness 和没有 Harness 时，结果差异巨大。\n\n### Harness 的本质\n\nHarness 英文原意是\"马具\"——它的工程思想是：**确保模型能力被正确、稳定、可控地释放**，就像给大模型配上好的马具，让其力量得到有效控制。\n\n---\n\n## 二、Harness 工程四层架构\n\n```\n用户输入\n   ↓\n┌─────────────┐  不符合 → 拒绝/转人工\n│   约束层     │  符合 ↓\n│ (系统边界)   │\n└─────────────┘\n   ↓\n┌─────────────┐\n│   信息层     │  提供上下文信息（RAG、历史管理、知识注入）\n│ (上下文工程)  │\n└─────────────┘\n   ↓\n┌─────────────┐\n│   模型推理   │\n└─────────────┘\n   ↓\n┌─────────────┐  失败 → ┌─────────────┐\n│   验证层     │ ─────→ │   修正层     │\n│ (质量检验)   │        │ (保底机制)   │\n└─────────────┘        └─────────────┘\n   ↓ 通过\n  用户\n```\n\n### 1. 约束层 — 定义系统边界\n\n**核心功能：** 定义 AI 能做什么、不能做什么、做成什么样。\n\n**三类约束：**\n- **角色约束**：规定 AI 的身份（如\"亚信科技客服助手\"）\n- **输出格式约束**：规定输出必须是 JSON/某格式\n- **安全约束**：不能透露系统提示内容等\n\n**常见坑：**\n- 写得太宽 → 形同虚设\n- 写得太窄 → 影响用户体验\n\n> 设计要点：度的把握需在实际工程中反复调试。\n\n### 2. 信息层 — 提供任务所需的上下文\n\n**核心功能：** 为模型提供完成任务所需的上下文信息。\n\n**典型技术：**\n- RAG 检索注入（用户套餐信息等）\n- 多轮会话管理的裁剪和压缩策略\n- 业务知识知识库注入\n\n**关键原则：**\n\n> 信息要**刚好够且精准**——过多浪费 TOKEN 且引入噪音，过少则回答不准确。\n\n### 3. 验证层 — 输出质量检验\n\n**核心功能：** 在模型输出到达用户之前进行质量检验。\n\n**四类检查：**\n- **格式检查**：是否合法 JSON\n- **事实验证**：账单金额是否与数据库一致\n- **安全验证**：是否包含敏感信息\n- **一致性验证**：答案是否自相矛盾\n\n**验证失败决策策略：**\n- 直接拒绝回答\n- 降级到安全兜底回答\n- 转人工处理\n\n### 4. 修正层 — 保底机制\n\n**典型策略：**\n- **重试**：调整参数重新生成\n- **降级**：返回预设安全答案\n- **人工兜底**：置信度低于阈值转接人工\n- **反馈闭环**：收集触发修正的案例优化前三层\n\n**关键原则：**\n\n> 修正层是保底机制，**不应频繁触发**。若频繁触发，说明前三层存在问题。\n\n---\n\n## 三、各工程间的关系\n\n| 工程 | 解决的问题 | 作用域 |\n|---|---|---|\n| **提示工程** | 单次调用中如何写好 prompt | 一次 API 调用 |\n| **上下文工程** | 单次调用中如何给模型足够且准确的信息 | 一次或一轮调用 |\n| **Harness 工程** | 整个 AI 系统如何做稳 | 完整输入-输出链路 |\n\n**Harness 工程 = 提示工程 + 上下文工程 + 验证机制 + 修正机制 + 系统级安全约束**\n\n---\n\n## 四、实践案例\n\n### 案例 1：Anthropic 实验对比\n\n| 层级 | 无 Harness | 有 Harness |\n|---|---|---|\n| 约束层 | 无约束，agent 随意操作 | planner 形成包含 16 个功能的产品规格 |\n| 信息层 | 上下文窗口易被占满，早期设计易被遗忘 | 有上下文管理策略，agent 知道已做和待做 |\n| 验证层 | agent 自我感觉良好，实际输出质量差 | 独立 evaluator agent，发现代码隐藏 bug |\n| 修正层 | — | 发现问题后与 Generator 协商修正，多轮仍有问题则跳过保证进度 |\n\n**结论：** 加 4 层 Harness 后产出改善，虽成本提高 20 倍，但让产品从不可用到可用。\n\n### 案例 2：产品报价管理系统\n\n- **约束层**：编写宪法文件，规定技术栈边界（禁止使用 any 类型、禁止自定义 CSS 等）\n- **信息层**：每个 Sprint 开始时注入 spec、plan 和 progress 文件\n- **验证层**：设计独立 evaluator 角色，严格测试纪律（四项评估维度全部通过才认定 pass）\n- **修正层**：输出分级问题清单，Generator 修复后再验证\n\n### 案例 3：OpenAI Codex CLI\n\n- **约束层**：\"宁可少做、不要多做\"，绝不使用破坏性命令，不主动提交代码\n- **信息层**：设计 agents Markdown 文档机制，分层注入信息\n- **验证层**：由窄到宽的验证策略，先跑最相关测试，再扩大范围\n- **修正层**：格式修复最多重试三次，三次后放弃格式修复，提交功能正确代码并说明问题\n\n---\n\n## 五、用 Harness 四层诊断 AI 系统\n\n拿到一个 AI 项目，可以用四层框架来诊断：\n\n| 层级 | 诊断问题 |\n|---|---|\n| 约束层 | 有无明确角色边界？约束是否清晰可执行？ |\n| 信息层 | 模型能否获取业务数据？注入方式是什么？ |\n| 验证层 | 有无质量检查？检查哪些维度？ |\n| 修正层 | 有无重试机制？失败后如何处理？ |\n\n---\n\n## 六、后续学习\n\n- 课程明天继续：**规格驱动开发的框架**（Harness 工程在日常开发中的落地方法）\n- 思考作业：用 Harness 四层框架诊断你正在做或接触过的 AI 项目\n\n---\n\n## 七、关键语录\n\n> \"AI 应用从 Demo 到生产，关键不在模型，而在 Harness 工程。\"\n\n> \"修正层是保底机制，若频繁触发，说明前三层存在问题。\"\n\n> \"信息层提供信息要刚好够且精准，过多浪费 TOKEN 且引入噪音，过少则回答不准确。\"\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800894130}}
{"type":"message","id":"a3801660","parentId":"41dfd421","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:02:11.720Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great, I have the original notes from the course, plus now I have the GitHub information about modern Harness Engineering best practices. Let me create a comprehensive combined document that integrates both the lecture content and the open-source community best practices. I'll update the existing HARNESS_ENGINEERING.md with this new information.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_jj7h881l2q3q9vxbvx5dha1t","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace/HARNESS_ENGINEERING.md","oldText":"## 七、关键语录\n\n> \"AI 应用从 Demo 到生产，关键不在模型，而在 Harness 工程。\"\n\n> \"修正层是保底机制，若频繁触发，说明前三层存在问题。\"\n\n> \"信息层提供信息要刚好够且精准，过多浪费 TOKEN 且引入噪音，过少则回答不准确。\"","newText":"## 七、社区最佳实践（来自 GitHub 开源社区总结）\n\n### 架构原则\n\n1. **多代理模式，职责分离**：将工作分配给专门代理，而不是让单一代理过载。典型分工：\n   - **规划师 (Planner)**：将简短提示扩展为完整产品/功能规格，聚焦产品上下文和高级技术设计，而非颗粒化实现细节\n   - **生成器 (Generator/Builder)**：按规格一次实现一个功能，增量开发\n   - **评估者 (Evaluator/QA)**：像用户一样测试运行应用，根据标准对输出评分，并向生成器提供具体反馈进行迭代\n\n2. **保持单体直到复杂要求拆分**：在达到单一代理无法克服的特定瓶颈之前，先从单代理循环开始，不要过早引入多代理编排\n\n3. **每个会话重置上下文**：为每个会话创建新客户端/上下文，而不是仅依赖压缩。完整重置提供干净的状态，结构化工件衔接间隙\n\n### 状态管理与持久化\n\n- **状态持久化到结构化文件，而不是上下文**：任务列表使用 JSON（比自由格式 Markdown 更抗模型诱导损坏）、进度笔记、计划/规格文件、初始化脚本都需要写入磁盘\n- **使用仓库作为记录系统**：将所有相关知识推送到仓库，不能被代理发现的知识不存在\n- **AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md 应该是地图，而不是百科全书**：顶级指令文件保持简短（~100行），用作目录指向 `docs/` 目录中更深层的真实来源，渐进式披露知识\n\n### 会话协议\n\n- 每个会话遵循可预测的生命周期：定向 → 设置 → 验证基线 → 选择一个任务 → 实现 → 测试 → 更新状态 → 干净退出\n- **每个会话只处理一个任务**：防止上下文耗尽，保持每个会话专注和可恢复\n- **构建前先验证**：会话开始时始终运行基线验证，跨会话复合错误是最常见的失败模式之一\n\n### 反馈循环与反压\n\n- **自动化验证作为反压**：类型检查器、linters、测试套件、静态分析器、安全扫描器，关键约束：反馈轮必须快\n- **使用浏览器/UI 自动化进行验证**：强制代理与运行中的应用程序交互，捕获后端测试遗漏的错误\n- **构建具有具体评分标准的评估器**：不要问\"好不好\"，要定义具体的、可评分标准\n- **复杂工作使用 sprint 合同**：在每个实现块之前，生成器和评估者协商\"完成\"是什么样子\n\n### 上下文窗口管理\n\n- **将上下文视为稀缺资源**：将昂贵工作卸载给子代理，确定性地每次循环加载相同核心文件，指导代理在实现前搜索以避免重复实现\n- **战略性使用子代理**：只读操作（搜索、分析）扇出并行，写操作（构建、测试）限制并行性避免反压问题，让子代理汇总结果而不是将原始输出转储到主上下文\n\n### 安全与沙箱\n\n深度防御三层：\n1. **OS 级沙箱** — 隔离代理执行环境\n2. **文件系统限制** — 将文件操作限制在项目目录\n3. **命令允许列表** — 只允许代理需要的命令，对敏感命令添加验证\n\n### 代码质量与架构\n\n- **机械地强制执行不变量，而不是仅通过文档**：使用 linters、结构测试和 CI 检查来强制执行架构规则，自定义 lint 错误消息应包含修复说明\n- **技术债务视为垃圾收集**：运行定期清理代理扫描偏离\"黄金原则\"的地方，以小增量持续偿还债务，而不是让它复利\n- **优化代理可读性，而不仅仅是人类可读性**：支持\"无聊\"技术（可组合、稳定 API，训练数据中充分表示），而不是难以让代理建模的前沿技术\n- **让应用程序可被代理检查**：每个 git worktree 启动应用程序以便代理可以运行隔离实例，将浏览器 DevTools 协议连接到代理运行时，通过可查询 API 公开日志、指标和追踪\n\n### 恢复能力\n\n- **Git 是你的安全网**：每个成功任务后使用描述性消息提交，会话开始时读取最近 git 历史记录，使用 git 标签标记已知良好状态，代理生成损坏代码库时 `git reset --hard` 到最后一个良好状态重新运行\n- **预期失败并为之计划**：你会醒来看到损坏的构建，问题总是：重置重新运行更容易，还是制作提示拯救当前状态更容易？两种策略都有效\n- **定期重新生成计划**：待办事项列表和计划会随时间漂移，定期让代理将当前代码库与规范进行比较，删除并重新生成它们，防止代理遵循陈旧或不正确的计划\n\n## 八、关键语录\n\n> \"AI 应用从 Demo 到生产，关键不在模型，而在 Harness 工程。\"\n\n> \"修正层是保底机制，若频繁触发，说明前三层存在问题。\"\n\n> \"信息层提供信息要刚好够且精准，过多浪费 TOKEN 且引入噪音，过少则回答不准确。\"\n\n> **核心原则总结（来自社区）**：\n> 1. 上下文窗口是约束；结构化工件是解决方案\n> 2. 分离生成与评估 — 代理无法客观判断自己的工作\n> 3. 每个会话一个任务 — 专注防止上下文耗尽，保持会话可恢复\n> 4. 构建前验证 — 始终检查上一个会话没有破坏东西\n> 5. 接入快速反馈循环 — 测试、linters、类型检查和 UI 自动化作为反压\n> 6. 仓库是唯一真实来源 — 如果不在仓库中，对代理就不存在\n> 7. 人类掌舵，代理执行 — 工程师设计环境，指定意图，构建反馈循环，代理编写代码\n> 8. 期望最终一致性 — 大多数问题可以通过更好调优提示的更多循环解决\n> 9. 不断简化 — 剥去模型不再需要的线束复杂性"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":18716,"output":1542,"cacheRead":28472,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48730,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775800894132,"responseId":"chatcmpl-889effaf-518a-4e18-b136-a9a1e4053ede"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a67f5d5d","parentId":"a3801660","timestamp":"2026-04-10T06:02:11.734Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_jj7h881l2q3q9vxbvx5dha1t","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace/HARNESS_ENGINEERING.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 171 - 思考作业：用 Harness 四层框架诊断你正在做或接触过的 AI 项目\n 172 \n 173 ---\n 174 \n-175 ## 七、关键语录\n+175 ## 七、社区最佳实践（来自 GitHub 开源社区总结）\n 176 \n+177 ### 架构原则\n+178 \n+179 1. **多代理模式，职责分离**：将工作分配给专门代理，而不是让单一代理过载。典型分工：\n+180    - **规划师 (Planner)**：将简短提示扩展为完整产品/功能规格，聚焦产品上下文和高级技术设计，而非颗粒化实现细节\n+181    - **生成器 (Generator/Builder)**：按规格一次实现一个功能，增量开发\n+182    - **评估者 (Evaluator/QA)**：像用户一样测试运行应用，根据标准对输出评分，并向生成器提供具体反馈进行迭代\n+183 \n+184 2. **保持单体直到复杂要求拆分**：在达到单一代理无法克服的特定瓶颈之前，先从单代理循环开始，不要过早引入多代理编排\n+185 \n+186 3. **每个会话重置上下文**：为每个会话创建新客户端/上下文，而不是仅依赖压缩。完整重置提供干净的状态，结构化工件衔接间隙\n+187 \n+188 ### 状态管理与持久化\n+189 \n+190 - **状态持久化到结构化文件，而不是上下文**：任务列表使用 JSON（比自由格式 Markdown 更抗模型诱导损坏）、进度笔记、计划/规格文件、初始化脚本都需要写入磁盘\n+191 - **使用仓库作为记录系统**：将所有相关知识推送到仓库，不能被代理发现的知识不存在\n+192 - **AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md 应该是地图，而不是百科全书**：顶级指令文件保持简短（~100行），用作目录指向 `docs/` 目录中更深层的真实来源，渐进式披露知识\n+193 \n+194 ### 会话协议\n+195 \n+196 - 每个会话遵循可预测的生命周期：定向 → 设置 → 验证基线 → 选择一个任务 → 实现 → 测试 → 更新状态 → 干净退出\n+197 - **每个会话只处理一个任务**：防止上下文耗尽，保持每个会话专注和可恢复\n+198 - **构建前先验证**：会话开始时始终运行基线验证，跨会话复合错误是最常见的失败模式之一\n+199 \n+200 ### 反馈循环与反压\n+201 \n+202 - **自动化验证作为反压**：类型检查器、linters、测试套件、静态分析器、安全扫描器，关键约束：反馈轮必须快\n+203 - **使用浏览器/UI 自动化进行验证**：强制代理与运行中的应用程序交互，捕获后端测试遗漏的错误\n+204 - **构建具有具体评分标准的评估器**：不要问\"好不好\"，要定义具体的、可评分标准\n+205 - **复杂工作使用 sprint 合同**：在每个实现块之前，生成器和评估者协商\"完成\"是什么样子\n+206 \n+207 ### 上下文窗口管理\n+208 \n+209 - **将上下文视为稀缺资源**：将昂贵工作卸载给子代理，确定性地每次循环加载相同核心文件，指导代理在实现前搜索以避免重复实现\n+210 - **战略性使用子代理**：只读操作（搜索、分析）扇出并行，写操作（构建、测试）限制并行性避免反压问题，让子代理汇总结果而不是将原始输出转储到主上下文\n+211 \n+212 ### 安全与沙箱\n+213 \n+214 深度防御三层：\n+215 1. **OS 级沙箱** — 隔离代理执行环境\n+216 2. **文件系统限制** — 将文件操作限制在项目目录\n+217 3. **命令允许列表** — 只允许代理需要的命令，对敏感命令添加验证\n+218 \n+219 ### 代码质量与架构\n+220 \n+221 - **机械地强制执行不变量，而不是仅通过文档**：使用 linters、结构测试和 CI 检查来强制执行架构规则，自定义 lint 错误消息应包含修复说明\n+222 - **技术债务视为垃圾收集**：运行定期清理代理扫描偏离\"黄金原则\"的地方，以小增量持续偿还债务，而不是让它复利\n+223 - **优化代理可读性，而不仅仅是人类可读性**：支持\"无聊\"技术（可组合、稳定 API，训练数据中充分表示），而不是难以让代理建模的前沿技术\n+224 - **让应用程序可被代理检查**：每个 git worktree 启动应用程序以便代理可以运行隔离实例，将浏览器 DevTools 协议连接到代理运行时，通过可查询 API 公开日志、指标和追踪\n+225 \n+226 ### 恢复能力\n+227 \n+228 - **Git 是你的安全网**：每个成功任务后使用描述性消息提交，会话开始时读取最近 git 历史记录，使用 git 标签标记已知良好状态，代理生成损坏代码库时 `git reset --hard` 到最后一个良好状态重新运行\n+229 - **预期失败并为之计划**：你会醒来看到损坏的构建，问题总是：重置重新运行更容易，还是制作提示拯救当前状态更容易？两种策略都有效\n+230 - **定期重新生成计划**：待办事项列表和计划会随时间漂移，定期让代理将当前代码库与规范进行比较，删除并重新生成它们，防止代理遵循陈旧或不正确的计划\n+231 \n+232 ## 八、关键语录\n+233 \n 177 > \"AI 应用从 Demo 到生产，关键不在模型，而在 Harness 工程。\"\n 178 \n 179 > \"修正层是保底机制，若频繁触发，说明前三层存在问题。\"\n 180 \n 181 > \"信息层提供信息要刚好够且精准，过多浪费 TOKEN 且引入噪音，过少则回答不准确。\"\n+239 \n+240 > **核心原则总结（来自社区）**：\n+241 > 1. 上下文窗口是约束；结构化工件是解决方案\n+242 > 2. 分离生成与评估 — 代理无法客观判断自己的工作\n+243 > 3. 每个会话一个任务 — 专注防止上下文耗尽，保持会话可恢复\n+244 > 4. 构建前验证 — 始终检查上一个会话没有破坏东西\n+245 > 5. 接入快速反馈循环 — 测试、linters、类型检查和 UI 自动化作为反压\n+246 > 6. 仓库是唯一真实来源 — 如果不在仓库中，对代理就不存在\n+247 > 7. 人类掌舵，代理执行 — 工程师设计环境，指定意图，构建反馈循环，代理编写代码\n+248 > 8. 期望最终一致性 — 大多数问题可以通过更好调优提示的更多循环解决\n+249 > 9. 不断简化 — 剥去模型不再需要的线束复杂性","firstChangedLine":175},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775800931733}}
